sections.text:
We implemented a small subset of available Forth words in ∂4. The table of these words, together with their descriptions is given in Table 1. The commands are roughly divided into 6 groups. These groups, line-separated in the table, are:
Data stack operations 1+, 1-, DUP, SWAP, OVER, DROP Heap operations @, ! Comparators >, <, = Return stack operations >R, R>, @R Control statements IF..THEN..ELSE, BEGIN..WHILE..REPEAT,
DO..LOOP Subroutine control :, ;

0 : DIGIT+ 1 DUP 1 = IF >R 2 DUP 9 = IF 3 DROP 0 R> ELSE 1+ R> 1- 4 THEN 5 THEN 6 >R 7 BEGIN DUP WHILE 8 1- SWAP DUP 9 = IF 9 R> 1+ >R
10 DROP 0 11 ELSE 12 1+ SWAP 13 THEN 14 REPEAT 15 DROP 16 R> 17 ;
Listing 4: Full code for adding two digits and a carry. The code is long due to the fact that the adding of two numbers in Differentiable Forth is currently realised with multiple executions of 1+.
